data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for your test:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);  // or CollectionAssert.That is not built-in,
    // so use:
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User)); // type check
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)); // LINQ predicate still fine here

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key MSTest replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, list.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(false, list.Count == 0)` or keep `Assert.IsTrue` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |

**`CollectionAssert` members worth knowing:**

- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)`
- `CollectionAssert.DoesNotContain(collection, element)`
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — any order
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`

The main wins are `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` (gives you expected vs. actual in failure messages) and `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` (clearer intent). MSTest's `CollectionAssert` doesn't have a built-in predicate-based "all match" assertion, so `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` is acceptable there.
